Loop over the cells in the first row. Then loop over the remaining rows. Use `.includes()` to test if the name in the first cell of that row is in the value from the cell from the first row. If it is, replace it with the value from the second cell.

```
for (int col = 1; col &lt; 60; col++) {
    let name = activeSheet.getRange(1, col).getValue();
    for (int row = 2; row &lt; 50; row++) {
        if (name.includes(activeSheet.getRange(row, 1).getValue())) {
            activeSheet.getRange(1, col).setValue(activeSheet.getRange(row, 2).getValue());
            break;
        }
    }
}
```

**UPDATE**

**ON IOS** 
the answer is to **attempt to sign out the user before presenting the initial email sign up/in flow from FirebaseUI, so that the link that gets *sent* to their email does not contain a Anonymous UID field** 

(see below for details on why this is working (for me at least))


----------

**Some Details:**

I&#39;ve been working on debugging this nonstop since yesterday. So, for anyone coming across this very specific issue, I want to make some more things known about the context for above:

 1. The authentication actually worked fine if I deleted the account from Firebase, but only on the *first* sign in/up attempt.
 2. In general, I have the user always signed in as Anonymous until they sign up (in which case I let FirebaseUI either handle the auto upgrade or the usual sign in). 

The problem entered in that I made the assumption from (2) that FirebaseUI would handle the situation correctly for all authentication methods. For email link authentication, when the user initially inputs their email into the FirebaseUI flow, if they are Anonymous at the time, it will send an email link with a field/parameter that indicates their Anonymous User ID. If this field is present when the app is opened up again via a Dynamic Link, and that link received by the app is then sent to this method:
```swift
FUIAuth.defaultAuthUI()!.handleOpen(link, sourceApplication: bundleIdentifier)
```
what will happen is that it will try to auto upgrade the anonymous user to the email account. 


Now, for the first attempt on a new account creation, this works fine. But for subsequent attempts to use the firebase ui flow to authenticate the same email, it will try to auto upgrade an anonymous user into an account that already exists or something along those lines (the specifics will probably dictate whether this is actually a FirebaseUI issue, or if it is a FirebaseAuth issue, or if it is working as intended etc etc).


Obviously, if you rely on the data attached to a specific UID, this method will not work for you, as the UID is never preserved on email auth if you sign out the user from anonymous and then create/sign in with an email account.

If you need to preserve the UID before and after Auth or you cannot sign out the user without issue, AND you HAVE to use FirebaseUI, then I would recommend preventing the user from being able to sign out after they authenticate inside your app. This is not a great solution, so removing email authentication as a provider for FirebaseUI on iOS and relying on the other authentication providers might be better temporary solution. 

**All of the above are temporary solutions**

The FirebaseUI Team should already be aware of the issue via https://github.com/firebase/FirebaseUI-iOS/issues/741 (which I found out is actually exactly the issue I was facing, but I ignored this originally because I didn&#39;t think it was re-authentication at all). Hopefully they will be able to make some more headway on a fix for this issue soon. If I had any idea of how best to fix this inside their flow, I would make a PR myself, but since I don&#39;t I&#39;m going to just rely on this and wait.


----------


**What about *shouldAutoUpgradeAnonymousUsers = false*?**

Turns out, after looking at the code for FirebaseUI/Auth/FUIAuth.m, FirebaseUI/Email/FUIEmailAuth.m, and FirebaseUI/Email/FUIEmailEntryViewController.m, setting this flag to false during this entire process (sign up/in, send link, open link, handle link), will not change anything. If anything it will cause the entire flow to always fail. Since the user is anonymous on the initial email link send, it will still include the anonymous uid in the link, which in turn will cause the method that handles the url to run the method that handles upgrading of the anonymous user (since there is one that appears to &quot;need&quot; to be upgraded).

FUIEmailAuth.m 
```objc
- (BOOL)handleOpenURL:(NSURL *)URL sourceApplication:(nullable NSString *)sourceApplication {

...

 } else if (urlParameterDict[@&quot;ui_auid&quot;]) {
   [seld handleAnonymousUpgrade:urlParameterDict[@&quot;ui_auid&quot;] email:localParameterDict[kEmailLinkSignInEmailKey]];
 } else {

...

}
``` 

That method that handles that will then skip on the initial check because we are not upgrading anonymous users, which then tries to handle the situation as if the user opened the link on a different device (incorrect, at least in this case). Which simply doesn&#39;t let the user sign in.

FUIEmailAuth.m
```objc
- (void)handleAnonymousUpgrade:(NSString *)anonymousUserID email:(NSString *)email {
  // Check for the presence of an anonymous user and whether automatic upgrade is enabled.
  if (self.authUI.auth.currentUser.isAnonymous &amp;&amp;
      self.authUI.shouldAutoUpgradeAnonymousUsers &amp;&amp;
      [anonymousUserID isEqualToString:self.authUI.auth.currentUser.uid]) {

  ...

  } else {
    [self handleDifferentDevice];
  }
```

